  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I tell my neighbours before listing my Brisbane home?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, in almost every case. A short conversation or a hand-delivered note the week before the photographer arrives sets expectations about signage, open home traffic, and possible auction day logistics. Neighbours who hear from you first are far more likely to be cooperative through the campaign and far less likely to give critical or speculative information to buyers who door-knock them. The cost is fifteen minutes. The downside of skipping it is unpredictable."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do buyers actually door-knock neighbours during a Brisbane property search?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, more often than most sellers realise. Serious buyers in Brisbane's inner east, particularly those looking at houses over $1.5 million or planning a renovation, frequently knock on doors either side of a listing to ask about flooding, noise, the body corporate, building works, and how long the current owner has been there. What your neighbour says in that thirty second conversation can move a buyer's offer or kill their interest entirely. This is one of the strongest practical reasons to invest in the neighbour relationship before the campaign starts."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I need to resolve a boundary or fence dispute with my neighbour before selling in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If there is an active dispute, a Notice to Contribute under the Neighbourhood Disputes (Dividing Fences and Trees) Act 2011, a QCAT application, or an unresolved Order made under the Act, you must disclose the status under the Property Law Act 2023 seller disclosure regime. A lingering dispute will surface in buyer due diligence, will be mentioned by the neighbour if asked, and is almost always cheaper to resolve before listing than to argue about during a contract. Where resolution is not realistic before the campaign, get legal advice on the disclosure wording and price the property with the issue in mind."
      }
    }
  ]
};
